SOFTWARE USED: Ubuntu 18.04/ 20.04 and NS-2.34 simulator package. 

THEORY:  

1. Distance Vector Routing (DVR): 
Distance Vector Routing is a dynamic routing algorithm in which each router periodically 
exchanges routing information with its direct neighbors. It is one of the earliest routing 
techniques and forms the basis of protocols like RIP and DSDV. 
Each router maintains a routing table containing: 
● Destination network 
● Distance (usually hop count or cost) 
● Next-hop router 
This table represents the router’s “vector” of distances to all destinations. 
The DVR algorithm operates based on the Bellman-Ford equation: 
Distance(A, X) = min over all neighbors N [ Distance(A, N) + Distance(N, X) ]
Advantages 
● Simple and easy to implement. 
● Low computational complexity (no global map needed). 
● Requires less memory and processing. 
Disadvantages 
● Slow convergence in large networks. 
● Prone to routing loops. 
● Suffers from count-to-infinity problem. 
● Entire routing table is exchanged → high update traffic
2. Link State Routing (LSR) 
Link State Routing is a dynamic routing technique where every router builds a complete 
topology map of the network and uses Dijkstra’s Shortest Path Algorithm to compute the best 
routes.It forms the foundation for modern protocols such as OSPF, IS-IS, and OLSR. 
Each router discovers: 
● Its neighbors 
● Link costs 
● The full network topology (via flooding) 
This enables routers to compute optimal paths using graph algorithms.
Characteristics 
● Fast convergence 
● Topology awareness (global knowledge) 
● Updates are event-driven 
● Works well for large-scale networks 
●  
LSR Protocol Examples 
● OSPF (Open Shortest Path First) 
● IS-IS 
● OLSR (used in NS2 for wireless)

RESULT:  Both Distance Vector (DSDV) and Link State (OLSR) routing protocols were 
successfully implemented in NS2.
